728237f-a.text:
Wyckoff Ave., at the S.W. corner of Cooper Ave. (formerly Lawrence Street); showing the Norman Van Nostrand farmhogse from 1852-1860. This place was known as "The Little Pink House." Norman Van Nostrand came here from New York City. He settled on forty acres of land and erected this house thereon in 1852. This house which was demolished in 1910 was also known because the feast church services of the St. Thomas Episcopal Church (located on Bushwick Ave. and Cooper Street, Kings
County) were held here during the winter of 1871.
1909.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

726375f-a.text:
Cooper Ave., at S.W. corner of Wyckoff Ave., showing the home occupied by John E. Van Nostrand in 1873. This is a set of three views. No. 3 is on Wyckoff Ave. It was demolished in April 1929.
1909.
Views 2 & 3: March 1923.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

726376f-a.text:
Cooper Ave., at the S.E. corner of Wyckoff Ave., showing a house in the Cemetery of the Evergreens. The Queens Atlas of 1914 and 1929 show no house on this property. Hoeever, the Queens Atlas of
1909 does show this house at the above location.
May 1923.
